{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656003"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:08:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:08:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18705"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18705"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.86,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11437"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79465"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11437"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64787"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27184"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79465"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the menstrual cycle, several hormones coordinate to regulate follicular development and ovulation. A sudden surge in one particular hormone is responsible for triggering the release of the oocyte from the ovary.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is this hormone that triggers ovulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Follicle-stimulating hormone","Inhibin","Luteinising hormone","Oestrogen","Progesterone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELuteinising hormone\u003C/strong\u003E directly triggers ovulation through a sudden surge around day 14 of the menstrual cycle. This surge causes the dominant follicle to rupture and release its oocyte approximately 36 hours later.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollicle-stimulating hormone\u003C/strong\u003E stimulates follicular development and oestrogen production but does not directly trigger ovulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOestrogen\u003C/strong\u003E rises during the follicular phase and provides positive feedback to trigger the luteinising hormone surge, but does not directly cause ovulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgesterone\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily produced after ovulation by the corpus luteum and does not trigger the ovulatory process\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibin\u003C/strong\u003E provides negative feedback to suppress follicle-stimulating hormone but has no direct role in triggering ovulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe luteinising hormone surge also initiates luteinisation of the remaining follicular cells to form the corpus luteum, which will produce progesterone during the luteal phase of the cycle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The luteinising hormone surge triggers ovulation by causing rupture of the dominant follicle and release of the oocyte.","Follicle-stimulating hormone promotes follicular development but does not directly trigger ovulation.","Rising oestrogen levels during the follicular phase provide positive feedback to trigger the luteinising hormone surge."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64787"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18705"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64787"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T19:30:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T19:31:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11437"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79465"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd5a","name":"Reproductive System (Female)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG